  "text": "Wireless sensor networks constitute a potentially very important but also extremely challenging application area for formal methods. As we have seen in this paper, even the analysis of a basic clock synchronization algorithm for an industrial WSN turns out to be quite difficult. Formal analysis of the gossip layer is a largely unexplored research field [CITATION_1] . Using timed automata model checking, we discovered some interesting error scenarios for line topologies: for any instantiation of the parameters, the protocol will eventually fail if the network grows. We also succeeded in presenting a parametric verification for the very restrictive case of cliques (network with full connectivity). We used model checking to find the key error scenarios that underly the parameter constraints for correctness, and theorem proving to check the correctness of our manual invariant proof. In practical applications of WSNs, cliques rarely occur and therefore our results should primarily be seen as a first step towards a correctness proof for arbitrary and dynamically changing network topologies. Nevertheless, these results could give us an upper bound on allowable clock drift of a generic WSN.",
